                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d323">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">033.1100 Rogers, James H./33: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Adams</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-05-02T21:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 2, 1934—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 2—8 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Following for Morgenthau from Rogers. Chiang Kai-shek<note n="16"
                        xml:id="d323fn16">Chairman of Chinese Military Council and Commander in
                        Chief of Army, Navy, and Air Forces.</note> undertaking big program
                    agricultural rehabilitation. He stated to me Monday<note n="17"
                        xml:id="d323fn17">April 30.</note> that higher silver at this time by
                    further reducing agricultural prices would greatly retard this program. The
                    tendency of certain Government officials to favor Dies bill<note n="18"
                        xml:id="d323fn18">Congressman Martin Dies, of Texas, introduced a bill (H.
                        R. 7581) under which the Treasury Department would accept silver in payment
                        for exported farm surpluses; the House of Representatives passed it March
                        19.</note> apparently based purely on resulting profit from further use of
                    cotton and wheat loan. Because of illness Finance Minister Kung I have been
                    unable to discuss this with him. [Rogers.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Adams</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
